occurrenceRemarks: Alternately arranged, cordate foliage. The foliage‚Äôs underside (mostly in new growth) is covered in matted pubescence. 2 Forking tendrils adhere the vine growth to trees and other climbing surfaces, leaving behind a drier, much curlier old tendril. Small white flowers give way to dark purple grapes (berry fruit). Newer growth stems are pale green with pubescence, older growth becomes woody and cracks. Prefers sandier soils, typically grows along woodland borders or in thickets. Vitis labrusca is the species from which the popular Concord grape was cultivated.
